Frequent in Proper· tius (9 exx.) aedona-posses . . . displiceas: the sudden shift from posses (optat. subjunctive, imperfect of the wish with adverse decision, Gilder- sleeve-Lodge, 261 a.) to displiceas (optative present subjunctive without adverse decision) reflects the lover's varying moods of hope and despair and is not uncommon in poetry and in the animated discourse of a quiet-witted and impressionable racc, cp, 1, 4, 63 ; 2, 4, 7-10 and notes. -unl mihi r i.e. ‘soli mihi! So always in the undisputed work of Tibullus but never in Lygd. and the Pan. Messal. The frequency of unus in Propertius (over 70 exx.) amounts to apersonal peculiarity, but with him unsar = solus is comparatively rare- bella: see 1, 9, 71 n.; Ovid, Amor. 1, 9, 6. firmosus is found in all styles, bellus is popular, and its presence here suggests the epigram and Catullus. ⁸
